# PDF Character Sheet Export

## Rule: New features must be in the test PDF

When adding **any new PDF form field** or section:

1. **Implement filling** in the appropriate `fill*` method in `CharacterSheetPdf.scala` (e.g. `fillCombatStats`, `fillHeader`, `fillProficienciesAndFeatures`).
2. **Ensure the test PDF exercises it**: `testPdf()` (exposed as `window.testPdf`) uses `generateTest()` which builds a single test character and calls `generate(ch)`. The test character must have data that populates every section we fill, so new fields are never left untested.
3. **Update the test character** in `generateTest()` if a new field requires specific data (e.g. a new combat stat, a new checkbox group). Keep the test character comprehensive: header, combat (AC, HP, **hit dice**, prof bonus, init, speed, size), abilities, saves, skills, armor, weapons, spellcasting, currency, weapon/tool prof, feats, equipment, species traits, class features.

## Hit dice

Hit dice is filled in `fillCombatStats` as `{level}d{hitDie.sides}` (e.g. `1d10` for level 1 Fighter). The test character (level 1 Fighter) therefore exercises hit dice as `1d10`.

## Key files

| File | Purpose |
|------|--------|
| `common/pdf/CharacterSheetPdf.scala` | Form filling logic, `generate()`, `generateTest()` |
| `common/pdf/PdfLib.scala` | pdf-lib facade (setText, setFontSize, removeMaxLength, etc.) |

## Test PDF version stamp

`CharacterSheetPdf.testPdfVersion` is an integer appended to the test character's name (e.g. `Thorn Ironfist v3`). **Every change to PDF filling logic must bump `testPdfVersion`** so the downloaded PDF is immediately distinguishable from stale builds. If you forget, the user cannot tell whether they're looking at an old cached PDF or the latest code.

## Spell row visual order

The PDF template renders spell rows in a non-sequential field order: bare, 0, 1, then groups of three reversed (4,3,2), (7,6,5), … (28,27,26). `PdfFormFields.spellRowVisualOrder` maps visual position → field index. **Always use `spellName(visualPos)` / `spellLevel(visualPos)`** — never construct field names from raw indices.

## Checkbox mapping (CRITICAL)

The 5e2024 character sheet PDF has **no "prepared" checkbox column**. The spell table title is "CANTRIPS & PREPARED SPELLS" — being listed IS being prepared. Instead, prepared spells get a `[ ]` text prefix in the name field for the player to mark with a pen.

All checkboxes in the spell area are one of:
- **Expended spell slot diamonds** (Check Box37–58, at y ≈ 650–680): Never touch these — they are for the player during play.
- **C/R/M diamonds** (Check Box0 + 59–150 minus 149, at x ≈ 239/261/283): Concentration, Ritual, and Required Material indicators per spell row. Not filled by our code.

**Never call `check()` or `uncheck()` on any checkbox in the 37–150 range.** The only checkboxes our code touches are saves (0–25), armor proficiency (33–36), and skills (2–24). Run `mapCheckboxPositions()` in the browser console to re-verify positions if the template PDF changes.

## Exposing new JS functions

`@JSExportTopLevel("fnName")` in Scala.js is not enough. You must also add the import and `window.fnName = fnName` in `export-wrapper.js`, or the function won't be accessible from the browser console.

## Running the test

In the browser console: `testPdf()`. Downloads a filled PDF for the test character so you can verify layout and font sizes without creating a character in the app. Check the character name includes the expected version number to confirm you're seeing the latest build.
